Sequel joins.

Spark supports all six join types in sequel, and they carry exactly the same meaning as the dataframe how-argument from the transformations module. Only the syntax changes.

Let's walk them. An inner join returns only the rows that match in both tables. A left join keeps every row from the left table, filling nulls where the right side has no match. A right join is the mirror — every right row, nulls on the left. A full outer join keeps everything from both sides, with nulls wherever there is no match.

Then there are two special ones that people forget. A left semi join returns the left rows that have a match on the right, but it brings back no columns from the right table. Think of it as a filter — keep the left rows that have a partner. And a left anti join is the opposite — it returns the left rows that have no match on the right at all. That one is perfect for "find the customers who have never transacted."

The semi and anti joins are worth memorizing, because they express "exists" and "does not exist" intent directly, and they avoid pulling in right-side columns you do not want.
